First form the coefficient matrix and its determinant  
A = \begin{pmatrix}11&9&2\\7&5&3\\4&3&1\end{pmatrix},  
D = det A  
  = 11·det\begin{pmatrix}5&3\\3&1\end{pmatrix} 
   −9·det\begin{pmatrix}7&3\\4&1\end{pmatrix} 
   +2·det\begin{pmatrix}7&5\\4&3\end{pmatrix}  
  = 11·(5·1−3·3) −9·(7·1−3·4) +2·(7·3−5·4)  
  = 11·(−4) −9·(−5) +2·1  
  = −44+45+2  
  = 3  

Next form Dₓ by replacing the x‐column with the constants (−9,−7,−3):  
Dₓ = det\begin{pmatrix}−9&9&2\\−7&5&3\\−3&3&1\end{pmatrix}  
   = −9·det\begin{pmatrix}5&3\\3&1\end{pmatrix} 
    −9·det\begin{pmatrix}−7&3\\−3&1\end{pmatrix} 
    +2·det\begin{pmatrix}−7&5\\−3&3\end{pmatrix}  
   = −9·(5·1−3·3) −9·(−7·1−3·(−3)) +2·(−7·3−5·(−3))  
   = −9·(−4) −9·(−7+9) +2·(−21+15)  
   = 36 −9·2 +2·(−6)  
   = 36−18−12  
   = 6  

So x = Dₓ/D = 6/3 = 2.  

Form Dᵧ by replacing the y‐column with (−9,−7,−3):  
Dᵧ = det\begin{pmatrix}11&−9&2\\7&−7&3\\4&−3&1\end{pmatrix}  
   = 11·det\begin{pmatrix}−7&3\\−3&1\end{pmatrix} 
    −(−9)·det\begin{pmatrix}7&3\\4&1\end{pmatrix} 
    +2·det\begin{pmatrix}7&−7\\4&−3\end{pmatrix}  
   = 11·(−7·1−3·(−3)) −(−9)·(7·1−3·4) +2·(7·(−3)−(−7)·4)  
   = 11·2 −(−9)·(7−12) +2·(−21+28)  
   = 22 −(−9·(−5)) +2·7  
   = 22 −45 +14  
   = −9  

So y = Dᵧ/D = −9/3 = −3.  

Finally D_z by replacing the z‐column with (−9,−7,−3):  
D_z = det\begin{pmatrix}11&9&−9\\7&5&−7\\4&3&−3\end{pmatrix}  
   = 11·det\begin{pmatrix}5&−7\\3&−3\end{pmatrix} 
    −9·det\begin{pmatrix}7&−7\\4&−3\end{pmatrix} 
    + (−9)·det\begin{pmatrix}7&5\\4&3\end{pmatrix}  
   = 11·(5·(−3)−(−7)·3) −9·(7·(−3)−(−7)·4) −9·(7·3−5·4)  
   = 11·(−15+21) −9·(−21+28) −9·1  
   = 11·6 −9·7 −9  
   = 66 −63 −9  
   = −6  

So z = D_z/D = −6/3 = −2.  

