First form the coefficient‐matrix and compute its determinant  
A = \begin{pmatrix}2&3&1\\1&1&1\\3&4&2\end{pmatrix}  
\det A
=2\begin{vmatrix}1&1\\4&2\end{vmatrix}
-3\begin{vmatrix}1&1\\3&2\end{vmatrix}
+1\begin{vmatrix}1&1\\3&4\end{vmatrix}  
=2(1·2−1·4)−3(1·2−1·3)+(1·4−1·3)  
=2(−2)−3(−1)+(1)  
=−4+3+1=0.  

Since \det A=0, Cramer’s Rule does not give a unique solution.  In fact if you subtract the second equation from the first you get  
x+2y=3,  
and from x+y+z=9 ⇒ z=9−x−y.  Substituting into 3x+4y+2z=20 leads to the contradiction 21=20.  

Conclusion: the system is inconsistent and has no solution.
